Whenever I make public statements – no matter what I’m actually saying – a whole insulting tirade follows on social media, where it calls for recall, rejection of moderate politics, claims that I don’t belong to the Labour Party.
Like it doesn't just happen to me.
As a matter of fact, I know that I was even more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since the comments about me are at least mostly of a political nature.
I can only admire the professionalism and purposefulness of those colleagues who face sexist or racist squabbles every day without being afraid of them.
One of the biggest disappointments of this era in politics is how such insults have become the norm.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said Labour must embrace a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that the party is far from broad-minded, with every sign of mistrust or change in the rules of choice becoming more and more narrow-minded.
Over the past two years, I have received a lot of advice to calm down, not to talk so much and then “everything will be fine”.
But that’s not why I got into politics.
Ever since I joined Labour 32 years ago as a student provoked by Thatcher’s government, which through neglect led to the literal collapse of my excellent school, I have fought for better public services for those who need them most – whether as a local councilor or as a minister.
I never hid my political views, including during the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could be confused in any way by my political position and my disagreement with the current leadership.
To all those who supported the proposal on Friday, I would like to say that when the state rushes to Brexit, it will harm households, businesses and the public sector, and I do not understand the desire to waste my time and energy in loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But in reality my message is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are Labour members or not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threat of recall or political excommunication will refuse me to act in the way I consider best to protect your interests.
Chrissy Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
