John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, continuing in 2018 with another superb performance of exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports disciplines, the arts, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Association (SCIS), aim to offer the best level of education to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen career and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can draw up and implement a personal curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, your words will reach them.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are the first with the highest success for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high grade of A.
The data, which was collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students achieved an A grade in Chinese, with 72% of German learners having the same grade, 69% of French learners and 63% of Spanish learners having the same grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject of free choice on the part of students receive the same attitude as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission showed that, of the reasons why employers find it difficult to find employees, 17% indicated insufficient language competences.
Therefore, more and more knowledge of foreign languages is becoming mandatory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more jobs require a command of a foreign language, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person mastered a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill, which remains for life.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person in front of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak a language, with French being the only language with a double digit rate of 15%.
That is why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Proficiency in several languages, especially those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, every school will differ from the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages deemed more important to the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever interests your child has, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, as teachers will be specialists in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country, which requires this to be taken into account in the education system.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellence, to young people in Scotland.
I'll be honest with you.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
