North Korea says ‘no way’ to disarm unilaterally, without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepen mistrust of the United States and there is no way the country could unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
At the annual general assembly of the world organization, Ri Yong-hou said that over the past year "significant measures of good will" have been taken, for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests, destroying the nuclear test site and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we will not believe in our own national security and under no circumstances will we be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri expressed North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to nuclear disarmament, in which North Korea would be rewarded for taking step-by-step measures, his statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work for “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump gave guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘elimination of nuclear weapons first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and even objects to the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a meaningless dream of those who do not know us.
The problem, however, is that continued sanctions are deepening our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention whether a second meeting between Kim and Trump was planned, which the U.S. leader stressed at the U.N. earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the country on the issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea, not the United States, the elimination of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill.
However, Ri’s tone of speech was markedly different from the previous year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that directing North Korean missiles at the U.S. mainland was inevitable after the “evil president” Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened North Korea with “total destruction,” praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea removed its nuclear weapons.
