Students at Harvard on a course for sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University this year causes all students to sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning “all night” with the help of caffeine.
A lecturer found that students at the world’s number one university often don’t even think about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, prepared the course he believes to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“Finally, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is taking place for the first time this year, explains to students the essentials of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students suffered from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm room where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers, and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of bedtime routines.
Another part of the participants told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of your choice to smoke.”
The culture of pride in “learning all night long” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Getting enough quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he says — even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Keisler prepare the course by taking one of his classes in his first year at Harvard.
He says the course “opened his eyes” and inspired him to spread it throughout the campus.
It hopes that the next step is for all graduates to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Keisler recommends that students think about setting up a bedtime and wake-up alarm, and know the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
