World Wide Web inventor plans to launch new internet to attack Google and Facebook
World Wide Web inventor Tim Berners-Lee is launching a venture that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that builds the Berners-Lee Solid open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people have permission to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intent behind Inrupt was "world domination".
"We have to do it now," he said of the venture.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “online personal data store” or POD.
It contains lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It is similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, which are available through any browser, and at the same time it is all of them at the same time.
What is unique about the online personal data repository is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it “giving authority to personal data.”
The idea behind Inrupt, according to company CEO John Bruce, is for the company to invest resources, processes, and appropriate skills to help Solid become accessible to all.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, several developers contracted to work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, tech developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not to make a complete change when all their business models are completely updated overnight.
“We don’t want permission from them.”
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s mission is to provide energy for commerce and the ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had a strong influence in the net neutrality debate.
Despite the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I am extremely optimistic about this new era of the internet,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Van: in memory of the priest awarded the Victoria Cross in the First World War
It marks 100 years in the home town of the only Anglican priest to be awarded the Victoria Cross for his service in World War I.
Lt. Col. Bernard Vann won the award on 29 September 1918 in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper, not realizing that he had been awarded the highest military honors in Britain.
A memorial was unveiled Saturday by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Van, said it was “extremely symbolic” that the monument be unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s medal-winning work.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lt. Col. Van led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very thick fog and under heavy artillery and machine gun fire."
He later attacked the firing line and with "incredible bravery" led the line forward before attacking an artillery piece with one hand and killing three of the squad.
Lt. Col. Wang was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I could never do, but it makes me humble.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, put on a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said it was "a great honor to participate in the parade" and added "the true hero's virtue is demonstrated through the support that will be given to many people."
MMA fans waited all night to watch Bellator 206, but instead got Peppa Pig
Imagine waiting all night to watch a full edition of the Bellator 206 and finally not being able to witness the main event.
The program from San Jose contained 13 matches, including six from the main map, and had to be broadcast live at night in the UK on Channel 5.
At 6 a.m., just as Geghard Musashi and Rory McDonald were preparing to face each other, viewers in the UK were stunned when the show changed to Peppa Pig.
Some were disappointed after waking up to the early hours, especially because of the match.
Fan described the switch to the children’s animated film on Twitter as “some sick joke.”
“The government regulates that at 6 a.m. this content is not appropriate, so the program was replaced with a children’s show,” Dave Schwartz, Bellator’s senior vice president of marketing and communications, said in response to a question about the broadcast.
"Peppa pig," yes.
Bellator president Scott Cocker said he would work on scheduling the meetings to include viewers from the UK in the future.
“In my opinion, when it comes to repetitions, we can solve the problem,” Cocker said.
“But it’s six in the morning on Sunday and we can’t plan things so that here the event takes place on Sunday, and there – on Monday.
We're working on it, though.
Believe me, when the program was changed, we received a lot of messages and not everyone was friendly.
We tried to fix it because we thought it was a technical problem.
But it wasn't like that. It was government.
I can promise you, next time it won't happen.
We will stick to the inclusion of five matches instead of six – as we usually do. We tried to give more to the fans, but we overdid it.
This is an unpleasant situation."
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daly felt 'lower' because of his sexuality
Olympic water-jumper Tom Daly says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone else because of his sexuality – but that motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old claims that until he started high school, he didn’t realize that “not everyone is like me.”
In an interview with the first edition of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, led by Lauren Laverne, he spoke about gay rights to give “hope” to others.
He also said that when he became a parent, he became less interested in winning the Olympics.
The longtime host of the show, Kirsty Young, has been in the hospital for several months.
On Laverne's first program, Daley said he felt "less" than everyone else when he was growing up because "it wasn't socially acceptable to like both girls and boys."
He said, “To this day, feeling inferior and being different from others are actually the things that give me the energy and strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove he was “something,” he said, so he wouldn’t disappoint anyone when he eventually learned about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist became an active participant in LGBT campaigns and used his participation in this year’s British Commonwealth Games in Australia to call for more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He said he was doing this because he was happy to be able to live openly, without consequences, and wanted to give “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion said that when he fell in love with a man - American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 - he was "surprised."
Daley married the Oscar-winning actor, who is 20 years his senior, last year, but says the age difference has never been a problem.
“When you go through so much while you’re so young” – he first participated in the Olympics at 14, and his father died of cancer three years later – he said – “it’s hard to find someone your age who has experienced similar ups and downs.”
The couple became parents in June and have a son, Robert Ray Black-Daily, who says his "whole worldview" has changed.
“If you had asked me last year, I would have told you that I was only interested in winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son was named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father couldn’t accept that he was going to die, and one of the last things he asked was whether they already had tickets to the 2012 London Olympics – because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You’re not going to be there for me, Dad, not even in the front row,’” he said.
“I held his hand until he stopped breathing and at that point when I found out he was dead, I finally admitted he wasn’t invulnerable,” he said.
The following year, Daly competed in the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
“I just knew that all my life I had dreamed about it – to jump at the Olympic Games in front of the audience at home. There was no better feeling,” he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song – “Proud” by Heather Small – which accompanied him during his preparation for the Olympic Games and still makes him cringe.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 a.m., British Summer Time.
Lost form Mickelson will stay on the bench for the Ryder Cup on Saturday
Phil Mikkelson will set a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th game in the Ryder Cup, but he will have to regain his old form if he does not want his record to be associated with failure.
Mickelson, who participated in the two-year event for the record-breaking 12th time, was left on the bench by captain Jim Furick for the fourball and fours games on Saturday.
Instead of once again being a major figure in the US team, the five-time winner of major tournaments spent his day as a fan and in training his shots from a distance in the hope of correcting his weaknesses.
The 48-year-old athlete, who has never been among the straightest players even at the height of his career, is not in optimal shape for Le Golf National’s difficult pitch, where long rough terrain usually punishes any mishit.
And if the pitch itself isn’t disturbing enough, in Sunday’s ninth game, Michelson will face precision British Open champion Francesco Molinari, who is teaming up with rookie Tommy Fleetwood and aiming to win all four of his games this week.
If the Americans, who are four points behind before the 12 games of singles, make a strong start, it may turn out that the match of Mikkelson is absolutely crucial.
Furik expressed confidence in his team-mate, although he could hardly say anything very different.
“He fully understood his role today, patted me on the back, hugged me and said he would be ready tomorrow,” Furik said.
“He is confident in himself.
He is a member of the Hall of Fame and has given so much both in the past and this week.
I didn’t expect him to play in only two games.
I expected him to play more, but it just happened and we believe that we made the right decision.
He wants to be on the golf course and play like everybody else.”
Mickelson will break Nick Faldo’s record for most Ryder Cup games played on Sunday.
This could put an end to his career in the Ryder Cup, which never came close to his impressive individual achievements.
Mikkelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven draws, but Furik said his presence brings other benefits to the team that are not measured in numbers.
“He’s funny, sarcastic, witty, likes to joke with people and is a great guy for any team,” he said.
“I think the younger players had fun with him, especially this week.
He gives a lot more than just playing.”
