Germany Delays Launch of New Warship
The German Navy’s newest frigate was due to be commissioned in 2014 to replace aging Cold War-era warships, but that won’t happen until at least next year due to faulty systems and skyrocketing costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the brand of new frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted a spokesman for the army.
The vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is understandable that they will have a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, e.g. reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the latest frigates should be able to be used for up to two years before returning to their home ports.
Continuous delays, however, mean that the vanguard warships — which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power overseas — will be old when they enter service, Die Zeit notes.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German navy officially refused to put the vessel into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have cited a number of significant "software and hardware defects" that make the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws are particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors – only half the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship was significantly overloaded, which reduces its efficiency and limits the ability of the Navy to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project – including crew training – is also becoming a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion ($3.6 billion) – up from the initial <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
Problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament’s defence committee, admitted that the fleet was actually “exhausting from ships capable of carrying out missions.”
The official said the problem had become bigger over time as the old ships were decommissioned but no new ones were provided.
He complained that no Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigate could join the fleet.
The National Trust tracks the secret life of bats
A new study, carried out in a mansion in the Scottish mountains, aims to find out how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats as well as the brown arrow-eared aquatic nightgowns at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key places in the mansion to track the activities of bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of invocational sounds of bats, as well as which species emit them.
After that, a habitat map and a report will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
Populations may be at risk from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, asylum inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization even created Scotland’s first and only special bat reserve at the Threat Manor in Dumfries and Galway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says it's perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threat, we have a great pitch for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, many old trees and a suitable habitat completed.
But there’s a lot more about bats that aren’t known, so the work we’re doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses that it is important to check for the presence of bats before property maintenance activities are carried out, as it is possible that the inadvertent destruction of a shelter will kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and about many of our animal species because we just don’t know what’s going on with their populations.”
Ronaldo Rejects Rape Claims and Lawyers Will Sue German Magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo described the rape allegations against him as "fake news", saying people "want to become famous" using his name.
