Mayorga also claimed she went to the police and had pictures taken of her injuries at the hospital, but later agreed to an out-of-court settlement because she felt “horrified of revenge” and worried about being “publicly humiliated.”
The 34-year-old woman says she wants to cancel the agreement as she continues to live with the trauma of the incident.
At the time of the incident, Ronaldo was on the verge of joining Real Madrid from Manchester United, and this summer moved to the Italian giant Juventus for the sum of 100 million euros.
Brexit: UK ‘will regret forever’ losing carmakers
LONDON (Reuters) - Britain will “regret forever” if it loses its status as a world leader in post-Brexit car manufacturing, business secretary Greg Clark said on Thursday.
He added that it was “worrying” that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if the UK left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at its plant in Burnaston, near Derby.
“We need a deal,” he said.
The Japanese carmaker said the impact of a delay at the border in the event of a no-deal Brexit could lead to job losses.
The Burnaston plant – where the Auris and Avensis models are produced – produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“My view is that if the UK leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our plant will stop,” said Marvin Cook, Toyota’s director at Burnaston.
Other UK carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have voiced concerns about leaving the EU without an agreement and how cross-border trade will work.
BMW, for example, says it will close its Mini plant in Oxford one month after Brexit.
The main concerns of car manufacturers are related to the risks to the supply chain in cases of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line operates on a “just-in-time” basis, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from both UK and EU suppliers for custom-made cars.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be problems at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and a shortage of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to wait more than a day to fill out its inventory at the Derbyshire plant, the company said, and so production would stop.
Mr Clark said Theresa May's "chess" plan for a future relationship with the EU was "precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks."
“We need to have a deal. We want to make the best deal that will allow us, as I say, not only to enjoy the current success, but also to be able to seize this opportunity,” he told BBC Radio 4’s Today programme.
“Following the claims not only of Toyota but also of other manufacturers, we are absolutely convinced that we should be able to continue to provide successful supply chains.”
Toyota cannot say how long production will be halted, but in the longer term they warn that the additional costs will reduce the plant’s competitiveness and ultimately lead to job losses.
Peter Tsvalaris, who has been working in Burnaston for 24 years and is the founder of the Unite union at the plant, said that its members are increasingly worried: “My experience is that if these jobs go away, they will never come back.
A government spokesman said: “We have set out a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU.”
Trump-Rosenstein meeting could be postponed again, White House says
WASHINGTON (Reuters) - A landmark meeting between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “delayed for another week” as the Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh’s fight continues, the White House said on Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Special Counsel Robert Mueller, who investigates Russian election meddling, ties between Trump aides and Russia, and the president’s potential obstruction of justice.
Whether Trump will fire the deputy attorney general or not, and thus threaten Mueller’s independence, has fueled rumors about Washington for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein was discussing the possibility of wearing a microphone to record conversations with Trump, as well as the possibility of removing the president through the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denies this claim.
But last Monday, he went to the White House after reports that he would resign.
Instead, while Trump was at the United Nations headquarters in New York, a meeting with him was announced for Thursday.
Trump said he would “prefer not” to fire Rosenstein, but the meeting was then postponed to avoid a conflict with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing, which was testified to by both Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual harassment – Dr. Christine Blaise Ford.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week-long FBI investigation into Kavanaugh’s complaints, further delaying a full Senate vote.
Trump’s spokeswoman, Sarah Sanders, appeared on Fox News on Sunday.
When asked about her meeting with Rosenstein, she said: “There’s still no set date for that, it could be this week, but seeing all the other things going on in the Supreme Court, I think it could be postponed to next week.
But we'll see, and I always try to keep the press informed."
Some reporters would dispute this claim: Sanders has not held a White House press conference since Sept. 10.
The show's host Chris Wallace asked about the reason.
Sanders responded that the rare press conferences were not due to dislike for the "demonstrative behavior" of television journalists, although he said: "I can't say I disagree with the fact that they have demonstrative behavior."
She then hinted that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
“The president has had more Q&A sessions than any president before him,” she said, adding without citing evidence: “We’ve checked these statistics.”
There will still be press conferences, Sanders continued, but “if the press has a chance to ask questions directly to the president of the United States, that’s far better than talking to me.
We try to do it often, and you've seen us practice it quite often in recent weeks, and that will replace press conferences once you have the opportunity to talk to the president of the United States."
Trump regularly answers questions when he leaves the White House or participates in open meetings or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
Independent press conferences are rare.
This week in New York, the president may have shown why, with his eccentric and at times strange behavior in front of the assembled journalists.
Health minister addresses EU workers at Scotland’s National Health Service over Brexit fears
The health minister wrote to EU staff working at Scotland’s National Health Service to express the country’s appreciation and desire for them to remain in their post-Brexit positions.
