Foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when buying real estate in the UK
Under new Conservative plans, foreign buyers will be charged a higher stamp duty when buying real estate in the UK, with additional funds to help the homeless.
This move will neutralize the success of Corbyn’s efforts to attract young voters.
The increase in the stamp duty will affect those who do not pay taxes in the UK
The Treasury is expecting an increase of over <0xC2><0xA3>120 million a year to help the homeless.
Theresa May will announce today the decision of foreign buyers to pay a higher stamp duty when buying real estate in the UK, with additional revenue going to help homeless people.
The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s efforts to attract young voters by promising more affordable housing and targeting high-income people.
The increase in the stamp duty will affect individuals and businesses who do not pay taxes in the UK, with the additional revenue helping the government’s efforts to limit the number of people sleeping on the street.
The supplement – which is in addition to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second homes and properties purchased for rent – could amount to up to three percent.
The Treasury expects revenues to rise by up to <0xC2><0xA3>120 million a year.
Around 13 per cent of newly built buildings in London are purchased by people with citizenship outside the UK, leading to higher prices and making it difficult for first-time buyers to intervene in the property market.
Many of the rich areas – especially in the capital – have become ghost towns, due to the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in the stamp duty to help more young people own their first home.
He accused major construction companies of maintaining high property prices by looting land but not using it, and asked Mrs May to abandon affordable housing quotas to fix Britain’s “shame on housing”.
Mr Corbyn announced an attractive series of housing reform proposals, including rent controls and an end to "no guilt" expulsions.
He also wants to give councils more power to build new homes.
Mrs May said: “Last year I shared that I would like to dedicate my time as Prime Minister to restoring the British dream of a better life for every new generation.
And that means fixing our broken housing market.
The UK will always be open to those who wish to live, work and build their lives here.
But it is not right for non-UK residents, as well as foreign companies, to buy homes as easily as hard-working UK residents.
For too many people, the dream of owning a home has drifted too far in time, and the insult of sleeping on the street remains too realistic.”
Jack Ross: 'My ultimate goal is to lead Scotland'
Sunderland manager Jack Ross said his "greatest ambition" in his career was to coach Scotland's national team.
The 42-year-old Scotsman accepted the challenge to revive the club from the north-east of England, which is currently in third place in the First League, three points from the first place.
