Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have been killed by a powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, authorities said, with the death toll expected to rise.
Due to the interruption of communications, support organizations are unable to obtain information from the Dongala Regency, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5 magnitude earthquake.
More than 16,000 people have been evacuated in Palu since the disaster.
Here are some basic facts about Palu and Dongala, which are located on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of central Sulawesi Province, located at the end of a narrow beach on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with a population of 379,800 people in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was hit by an earthquake and tsunami.
Dongala is a regency that extends more than 300 km (180 mi) along the coastline of Sulawesi Island.
The regency, which is an administrative region smaller than a province, has an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the foundations of the economy of central Sulawesi province, especially in the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important for the province, but is concentrated mainly in Morovali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Dongala have been hit several times by tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Disaster Recovery Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of buildings in Dongala.
The tsunami also hit the western part of Dongala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located on the seismic “Pacific Ring of Fire” and is regularly mowed down by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on 26 December on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in North Sumatra triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries and killed 226,000 people along the entire Indian Ocean coastline, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck the most populous island in Indonesia, Java, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake strikes near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake of magnitude 7.5 struck one of the islands of Mentawai and triggered a 10-meter tsunami wave that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake struck the Pidi Jaya Regency in Aceh, causing devastation and panic as people remembered the devastation from the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people were killed by collapsed buildings.
2018: Strong tremors hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, most of them on the northern side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily stranded.
