The first shots in the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while the battle is only gaining momentum, a rift between the two countries will benefit Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the US president, fired the first warning salvo this year, taxing key elements of China’s exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation of tensions came this week with new tariffs affecting US$200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) of output with effective taxation on half of all goods imported into the US from China.
Each time, Beijing retaliated with retaliatory new tariffs of five to 10 percent on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has vowed to retaliate against any U.S. strike, and soon the world’s second-largest economy is not expected to ignore that.
To force Washington to give up is to give in to demands, but to lower his head publicly before Washington would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
Still, according to experts, if Beijing plays its cards correctly, the pressure from the trade war with the United States could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a hasty political solution in both Washington and Beijing could create the conditions for an economic crisis in either country is actually more dangerous than observers have previously acknowledged,” said Abigail Grace, Asia-related research fellow at the Center for a New American Security expert group.
Syria 'ready' for return of refugees, foreign minister says
Syria has said it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for help in rebuilding a country ravaged by more than seven years of war.
Addressing the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Muallem said conditions in the country were improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress we have made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rebuild the areas ravaged by terrorists in order to return them to their normal state.
Now there are all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the war began in 2011.
Another six million people still living there are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Muallem said the Syrian regime would welcome any help in rebuilding the devastated state.
But he stressed that conditional aid or aid from countries that funded the rebels would not be accepted.
