New for the red tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manotti and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Committee shows a principal reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions for disruption of growth in the areas of Pinellas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier districts – this indicates a decrease in concentrations.
The watersheds with excessive red tide blooms extend approximately 130 miles along the coast, from the northern district of Pinellas to the southern district of Lee.
Algae patches can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but are smaller compared to last week.
Red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or slightly inward in Pinellas County, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, prerequisites for high concentrations in Manotti County, prerequisites for high concentrations in the coast or further inward in Sarasota County, prerequisites for moderate concentrations in Sarasota County.
Inflammation of the airways continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Over the past week, there have been no reports of airway inflammation in Northwest Florida.
